Here's an example of a regex pattern in Perl that matches most (but not all) valid UTF-8 encoded strings conforming to the syntax and format specified in RFC 5322:

```perl
#!/usr/bin/perl
use strict;
use warnings;

my $email_regex = qr/
    (?:(?:[\w!#$%&\*+\-/=?^\^_`{|}~-]+(?=\S*$)|"?(?:[\t\r\n]|[^:"?~])*$)?
     (?[IP_ADDRESS_1] (?=[[PERSON_1] KwLyPoFUeOivOWYbcXNHCGjfkSOZ])|\((?:(?:[a-zA-Z]|[0-9]|[$-@_\\+!*\\(\\),]|(?:%[0-9a-fA-F][0-9a-fA-F]))+)*(?:(?:\s,|(?=[a-zA-Z-]\.?&;:\.(?![\)\[:<>\/].*\.?[\w-]+)))?)?
     (?[IP_ADDRESS_2][PERSON_2]
   )+
/ix;

my $input = '[EMAIL_ADDRESS_1]';

if ($email_regex =~ /$input/i) {
    print "Valid Email: $input\n";
} else {
    print "Invalid Email: $input\n";
}
```

